==Awards and honours==
[[File:Medal of Arts award 2012.jpg|thumb|May receiving the Medal of Arts award from President Obama, July 13, 2013<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EciDRwKHONk&t=18m17s|title=President Obama Awards the 2012 National Medals of Arts and Humanities|first=|last=The Obama White House|date=10 July 2013|publisher=|accessdate=16 July 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>]]

May has received recognition for her writing, with her first [[Writers Guild of America]] nomination coming in 1971 for her debut film, ''[[A New Leaf (film)|A New Leaf]]'' (which she directed and in which she co-starred).<ref name=PetskiDeadline16>{{cite journal | author = Petski, Denise | year = 2016 | title = Elaine May To Receive WGA Screenwriting Honor | journal = Deadline Hollywood | issue = January 19 | format = online | page = | url = https://deadline.com/2016/01/elaine-may-wga-screenwriting-honor-laurel-award-2016-1201686055/ | access-date = 31 January 2016 | quote = Comedy screenwriter-director-actress Elaine May will receive the WGAW’s 2016 Laurel Award for Screenwriting Achievement at the WGA Awards L.A. ceremony on February 13. }}</ref> Further writing honours include an [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nomination for Best Adapted Screenplay, with Warren Beatty,<ref name=NYTheaven>{{cite journal | author = NYT Staff | year = 2010 | title = Heaven Can Wait (1978): Awards; Nominations | journal = [[The New York Times]] | issue =  | format = online | page = | url = https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/21978/Heaven-Can-Wait/awards | access-date = 31 January 2016 | quote = }}</ref> and similarly that years' [[Writers Guild of America]] award for ''[[Heaven Can Wait (1978 film)|Heaven Can Wait]]'' (1978).<ref name=PetskiDeadline16/> Other writing awards include a Saturn Award for Best Writing with Warren Beatty in 1978 for the same movie,<ref name=NYTheaven/> and a nomination for a [[Writers Guild of America|WGA]] for ''[[The Birdcage]]'' (1996),<ref name=PetskiDeadline16/> as well as a BAFTA Award for [[52nd British Academy Film Awards#Best Adapted Screenplay|Best Adapted Screenplay]] for ''Primary Colors'' (1998),<ref name=McNaryVariety16>{{cite journal | author = McNary, Dave | year = 2016 | title = Elaine May Honored by Writers Guild of America | journal = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] | issue = January 19 | format = online | page = | url = https://variety.com/2016/film/news/elaine-may-honor-writers-guild-1201682905/ | access-date = 31 January 2016 | quote = Elaine May will receive the Writers Guild of America West’s Laurel Award for Screenwriting Achievement to honor her career and body of work. }}</ref> and [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] and [[Writers Guild of America|WGA]] nominations for the same movie.<ref name=PetskiDeadline16/><ref name=McNaryVariety16/>

For her acting, her accolades include a nomination for a Golden Globe award for Best Actress in a musical or comedy for [[A New Leaf (film)|''A New Leaf'']] (1971),<ref name=DiMare>DiMare, Philip C. ''Movies in American History: An Encyclopedia, Volume 1'', ABC-CLIO (2011) pp. 738-739</ref> and winning the [[National Society of Film Critics]] Award for Best Supporting Actress for her role in ''[[Small Time Crooks]]'' (2000).<ref name=smalltime>[http://www.woodyallenmovies.com/movies/smalltimecrookstrivia.php Awards and Nominations for ''Small Time Crooks''], ''Woody Allen Movies</ref>

May was awarded the [[National Medal of Arts]] for her lifetime contributions by president [[Barack Obama]], in a ceremony in the White House on July 10, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2013/07/03/president-obama-award-2012-national-medal-arts-and-national-humanities-m|title=President Obama to Award 2012 National Medal of Arts and National Humanities Medal|author=|date=|work=whitehouse.gov|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref>

In January 2016, the Writer's Guild of America-West announced that May would receive its 2016 Laurel Award for Screenwriting Achievement at the Writer's Guild of America award ceremony in [[Los Angeles]] on February 13.<ref name=PetskiDeadline16/><ref name=McNaryVariety16/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ubypaJvPI0A|title=Screenwriter Robert Towne presents the 2016 Screen Laurel Award to Elaine May|first=|last=WGA West|date=14 February 2016|publisher=|accessdate=29 July 2018|via=YouTube}}</ref>
